&gt;Should I add an extra attribute to Card that hold that value? Or what do you think that could be a good way to go?

There is no absolute answer here. Context matters. 

As noted in the Comments, generally it is best to keep arbitrary presentation separate from content (&quot;model&quot;). But not if the desired presentation text is intrinsic to the entity represented by the data model.

 - If the presentation details could reasonably vary for various reasons, then your data model (the three classes you showed us) should *not* generate that particular value. Presentation text should be generated by some other class, not your data model classes (`Collection`, `Serie`, `Card`). For example, in the *java.time* classes, see the `DateTimeFormatter` class that generates arbitrary or complex text on behalf of the date-time classes such as `LocalDate`.
 - If that particular presentation text (collection id + serie name + card id) is canonical or standardized as a formal/official structure, then your data model classes (`Collection`, `Serie`, `Card`) *should* generate that text. For example, the *java.time* classes have a `toString` class that generates text in standard [ISO 8601][1] format, as well as a [`getDisplayName`][2] method to generate formatted text. 

So we cannot really answer your particular question, because we do not have an understanding of the domain from which you get your collection, serie, and card entities. 


----------

By the way, we can simplify that code. 

If your classes are meant primarily to be transparent carriers of shallowly-immutable data, then use [`record`][3] in Java 16+. The constructor, getters, `hashCode` &amp; `equals`, and `toString` are all implicitly created by the compiler. 

In Java 21+, you can use the more general interface `SequencedCollection` interface rather than `List`. See [*JEP 431: Sequenced Collections*][4].

As mentioned it Comments, `Collection` is the super-interface of the classes found in the [Java Collections Framework][5]. I would choose a different name if at all possible. If intrinsic to your domain, then just be careful with your `import` statements. 

Your Question’s code then becomes:

```java
class Collection ( String id , String name , SequencedCollection &lt; Serie &gt; series ) {}
```

```java
class Serie ( String id , String name , SequencedCollection &lt; Card &gt; cards ) {}
```

```java
class Card ( String id , String name ) {}
```

You can add additional methods to a record. If you decide your presentation text is intrinsic to your model, add a method named something like `getDisplayName`.

```java
class Collection ( String id , String name , SequencedCollection &lt; Serie &gt; series ) 
{
    public String getDisplayName() 
    { 
        StringBuilder stringBuilder = new StringBuilder() ;
        for ( Serie serie : this.series ) 
        { 
            for ( Card card : serie.cards )
            {
                stringBuilder
                    .append( this.id ) 
                    .append( &quot; | &quot; ) 
                    .append( serie.name ) 
                    .append( &quot; | &quot; ) 
                    .append( card.id ) 
                    .append( &quot;\n&quot; ) 
            }
        }
        return stringBuilder.toString() ;
    }
}
```


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/time/DayOfWeek.html#getDisplayName(java.time.format.TextStyle,java.util.Locale)
  [3]: https://openjdk.org/jeps/395
  [4]: https://openjdk.org/jeps/431
  [5]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_collections_framework

