The way this works is to consider that, conceptually, what you want is __identical__ to how the arabic numeric system works. i.e. how we count. What is the sequence of &#39;0, 1, 2, 3, 4, ...., 998, 999&#39; other than exactly what you&#39;re doing here?

Thus, the algorithm is clear:

* To start we begin at the beginning: `00000` in numbers, or, in this system, `aaaaaa` - the first character on every position. We call this &#39;the current value&#39;.
* We then add the current value and then replace the current value with its increment.
* To increment &#39;current value&#39;, we take the right-most character in it and replace it with the next character. This works.. until the right-most character has the same value as the last character in our set of chars. Then, just like &#39;99&#39; becomes &#39;100&#39;, we instead set this right-most character back down to the _first_ character in the set, and we aren&#39;t done incrementing yet - we now need to increment the next-to-right-most character. That one too could be at the final &#39;digit&#39; (9 in numbers, &#39;c&#39; in the code snippet), in which case, it, too, must be reset to &#39;a&#39; and we need to continue our incrementing algorithm.
* If this incrementing algorithm gets through the entire string, we just break as that means we&#39;re done: The only way we can go through the whole thing if is the string is ccccccc - every position has the final digit.

NB: I use binarySearch to find the index of the &#39;char&#39;, this only works if `chars` is sorted. If it isn&#39;t, you&#39;ll have to write a quick little &#39;find index&#39; method, or alternatively (if `chars` is very large, as in, over 500 or so characters, __and__ isn&#39;t sorted, then looking through it every time is slow, __only then__ go for this alternative): Instead of building characters in a StringBuilder, build up an array containing indices, not values. Now there is no need to look up where in the `chars` array the digit &#39;b&#39; shows up. Then the code to add to the list (which here is just `list.add(out.toString())` becomes much more complicated, but on the whole this would be algorithmically an order of magnitude or two faster.

