Let me point out a *few* mistakes in your code and question in general.

 1. Using `setBounds()`. It&#39;s just plain wrong. There is no point in having to be so specific every time you create a component, its unecessary, a waste of time and effort. There are so many [Layout Managers](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/layout/visual.html) that you are provided with just take advantage of that.
 2. However if you still want to use `setBounds()` because you are a menace to Swing you should remember you can&#39;t use `setBounds()` without setting layout to `null` with `frame.setLayout(null)`. Trying to use the `setBounds` method without setting the `null` layout just won&#39;t work.
 3. Using images instead of copying the code here on StackOverflow. I had to  manually copy this code line by line from an image wasting my time just so I could run it, please avoid using [pictures of code](https://meta.stackoverflow.com/questions/285551/why-should-i-not-upload-images-of-code-data-errors/285557#285557) as pointed out by [Diego Borba](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/77145322/jbutton-size-of-button-in-new-window-in-java-gui#comment135999190_77145322)

Instead of hard coding the position and sizing of your button (which is pointless as it will retain the same position from the top left corner of the JFrame) just use [GridBagLayout](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/layout/gridbag.html) because

 - It can keep the orientation no matter the size of the parent component
 - It is really customizable
 - It is also really easy to understand

