You should use `else if`, then you can apply the `continue` command:
```
Iterator&lt;Character&gt; sdf = d.iterator();
while (sdf.hasNext()) {
    Character r = sdf.next();
    if (r.equals(&#39;л&#39;)) {
        hg.add(k1);
    } else if (r.equals(&#39;р&#39;)) {
        hg.remove(k1);
    } else if (r.equals(&#39;g&#39;) || r.equals(&#39;d&#39;)) {
       continue;
    }
   
}

```

&gt; _&quot;... The main idea is to ignore words containing letters &#39;g&#39; and &#39;d&#39;. ...&quot;_

Qualify _r_ by asserting it is not _g_ or _d_, then delegate its value.

```java
if (!r.equals(&#39;g&#39;) &amp;&amp; !r.equals(&#39;d&#39;)) {
    if (r.equals(&#39;л&#39;)){
        hg.add(k1);
    }
    if (r.equals(&#39;р&#39;)){
        hg.remove(k1);
    }
}
```

It&#39;s typically a good idea to use a _switch statement_, when you have similar _if-statements_.

For example.

```java
if (!r.equals(&#39;g&#39;) &amp;&amp; !r.equals(&#39;d&#39;)) {
    switch (r) {
        case &#39;л&#39; -&gt; hg.add(k1);
        case &#39;р&#39; -&gt; hg.remove(k1);
    }
}
```

Alternately, you could add a _case_ for both _g_ and _d_, with an empty _code-block_.

```java
switch (r) {
    case &#39;g&#39;, &#39;d&#39; -&gt; { }
    case &#39;л&#39; -&gt; hg.add(k1);
    case &#39;р&#39; -&gt; hg.remove(k1);
}
```

This topic is referred to as _&quot;control-flow&quot;_.\
Here are some relevant links.

- _[Wikipedia &amp;ndash; Control flow](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_flow)_
- _[Control Flow Statements (The Java&amp;trade; Tutorials &amp;gt; Learning the Java Language &amp;gt; Language Basics)](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/flow.html)_

As a recommendation, the _for-loop_ on _k1_ can be simplified to a _stream_.

```java
d = k1.chars().mapToObj(x -&gt; (char) x).toList()
```

Or, just use a _char[]_ rather than a _String_.

```java
char[] k1 = hg.get(0).toCharArray();
for (char r : k1) {
    switch (r) {
        case &#39;g&#39;, &#39;d&#39; -&gt; { }
        case &#39;л&#39; -&gt; hg.add(new String(k1));
        case &#39;р&#39; -&gt; hg.remove(new String(k1));
    }
}
```

No need to use 2nd loop at all. You could use `String.indexOf()` instead.

Using functional programming
```java
public static List&lt;String&gt; filter(List&lt;String&gt; words) {
    return words.stream()
                .filter(word -&gt; {
                    word = word.toLowerCase();
                    return !(word.indexOf(&#39;g&#39;) &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; word.indexOf(&#39;d&#39;) &gt;= 0);
                })
                .collect(Collectors.toList());
}
```

